{
  "mcpServers": {
    "resonant-archive": {
      "command": "resonant-archive",
      "args": ["mcp"]
    }
  }
}

IMPORTANT NOTES:

1. This assumes you installed resonant-archive via pip and the
   `resonant-archive` command is on your PATH. Verify with:
     resonant-archive --version

   If the command is not found, use the full path to the script:
     - Windows: "C:\\Users\\YourName\\.venv\\Scripts\\resonant-archive.exe"
     - macOS:   "/Users/yourname/.venv/bin/resonant-archive"
     - Linux:   "/home/yourname/.venv/bin/resonant-archive"

2. You MUST start the daemon BEFORE opening Claude Desktop:
     resonant-archive serve

   Keep that terminal open. Close it with Ctrl+C when done.

3. Your actual Claude Desktop config lives at:
     - Windows: %APPDATA%\Claude\claude_desktop_config.json
     - macOS:   ~/Library/Application Support/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json
     - Linux:   ~/.config/Claude/claude_desktop_config.json

4. Add the "resonant-archive" block to your existing config's
   "mcpServers" object. Don't replace the whole file — merge in
   alongside any servers you already have.

5. Restart Claude Desktop COMPLETELY after editing the config
   (quit the app entirely, then reopen).

6. Once wired up, Claude Desktop will see two new tools:
     - archive_search(query, namespace?, n_results?)
     - archive_stats()

   Ask Claude "search my archive for X" and it'll call the right
   tool automatically.


Example of a complete config file with multiple MCP servers:

{
  "mcpServers": {
    "filesystem": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem", "C:\\allowed\\path"]
    },
    "resonant-archive": {
      "command": "resonant-archive",
      "args": ["mcp"]
    }
  }
}
